aws s3 ls | grep my-bucket-name

If nothing shows up, either you‚Äôre in the wrong region or it doesn‚Äôt exist. Add --region <region> if needed.

2) Transfer a single file

aws s3 cp /path/to/local/file.txt s3://my-bucket-name/

This will copy file.txt into the bucket root.
If you want to put it inside a folder:

aws s3 cp /path/to/local/file.txt s3://my-bucket-name/foldername/

3) Transfer a whole directory

aws s3 cp /local/directory s3://my-bucket-name/ --recursive

4) Keep directory in sync (useful for backups/deployments)

aws s3 sync /local/directory s3://my-bucket-name/
This only uploads new/changed files.

üí° Test first:
aws s3 sync /local/directory s3://my-bucket-name/ --dryrun
5) Transfer in the other direction (download from S3)

aws s3 cp s3://my-bucket-name/file.txt /local/path/

aws s3 sync s3://my-bucket-name/ /local/directory/

6) Useful options
--acl private ‚Üí force uploaded files to be private
--storage-class STANDARD_IA ‚Üí store as infrequent access
--exclude / --include ‚Üí control what files get uploaded

aws s3 sync /dir s3://bucket --exclude "*.tmp" --include "*.jpg"
‚úÖ Example: Upload a project folder to your existing bucket devops-s3-29232:

aws s3 sync ./project s3://devops-s3-29232/ --acl private

=========

1) Discover the command (no Google method)

aws ec2 help
Scroll until you find something like terminate-instances.
Check details:

 aws ec2 help | grep -i terminate
aws ec2 terminate-instances help

You‚Äôll see that it requires:
--instance-ids (one or more)

2) Get your instance ID

aws ec2 describe-instances \
    --query "Reservations[*].Instances[*].[InstanceId,State.Name,Tags[?Key=='Name']|[0].Value]" \
    --output table
3) Terminate the instance

aws ec2 terminate-instances --instance-ids i-0123456789abcdef0

4) Wait until it‚Äôs gone


aws ec2 wait instance-terminated --instance-ids i-0123456789abcdef0

5) Verify termination

aws ec2 describe-instances --instance-ids i-0123456789abcdef0

If it‚Äôs truly terminated, it won‚Äôt appear in active listings.

üí° Tips:
If you‚Äôre unsure, use --dry-run first:
aws ec2 terminate-instances --instance-ids i-0123456789abcdef0 --dry-run
Once terminated, the instance is gone forever ‚Äî you can‚Äôt ‚Äústart‚Äù it again; you‚Äôd have to launch a new one from an AMI or backup.
